{"title": "Building Local-First Flutter Apps with Riverpod, Drift, and PowerSync", "summary": "Building Local-First Flutter Apps with Riverpod, Drift, and PowerSync\n\nBuilding local-first Flutter apps with Riverpod, Drift, and PowerSync is a powerful approach to delivering seamless user experiences regardless of network conditions. By prioritizing local storage and handling synchronization in the background, these tools create a robust stack that makes local-first development approachable. In a traditional online-first app, data flows from the remote server to the local storage, but in a local-first app, the data flow is reversed, with changes applied locally first and then synchronized remotely. This shift means the local database becomes the primary source of truth, which has several implications, including the app reading from and writing directly to the local database, UI components reacting to changes in the local database, and synchronization running in the background, independent of user interactions. Building a sync engine is a complex task that requires careful management to minimize battery impact and handle edge cases like tracking all modifications that occur while a device is offline, handling conflicts when the same data has been modified in different ways across devices, and retry logic. PowerSync provides a solution for these synchronization challenges while integrating with Flutter's ecosystem, making it easier to build robust offline-capable apps.", "timestamp": 1746914750.3379269, "embedding": [-0.049499522894620895, -0.021687766537070274, 0.04251956567168236, -0.03098488226532936, -0.006109592504799366, -0.056972380727529526, -0.039837613701820374, -0.02128414623439312, 0.016242574900388718, -0.002115484792739153, -0.025656426325440407, -0.0021204522345215082, -0.009899524040520191, -0.06643582880496979, -0.01472808700054884, 0.0037652901373803616, 0.0935128852725029, -0.029764318838715553, -0.03528459370136261, 0.033651258796453476, -0.09816291